[[File:Bangladeshi girls taking Selfie at Pohela Falgun.jpg|thumb|Bangladeshi girls taking Selfie at Pahela Falgun festival.]]
{{Culture of Bangladesh}}
'''Pahela Falgun''' ({{lang-bn|পহেলা ফাল্গুন }}''Pôhela Falgun'' or পয়লা ফাল্গুন ''Pôela Falgun''), first day of [[Spring (season)|Spring]] of Bengali month [[Falgun]], of the [[Bengali calendar]], celebrated in [[Bangladesh]]<ref name=history>{{cite news|title=Pohela Falgun celebrated |url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=174151/ |newspaper=The Daily Star |date=14 February 2011}}</ref> it was started in 1991 by students of [[University of Dhaka|Dhaka University]]'s Faculty of Fine Arts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/falgun-celebration-how-it-all-began-1360324|title=Falgun Fest at DU: How it all began|date=2017-02-13|work=The Daily Star|access-date=2017-04-19|language=en}}</ref> The first of Falgun usually falls on 13 February of the [[Gregorian Calendar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nepcal.com/date_conv.php |title=Nepali Date Converter |publisher=banned-books.info |date= |accessdate=2013-06-21}}</ref> This day is marked with colourful celebration and traditionally, women wear yellow saris to celebrate this day. This celebration is also known as ''Basanta Utsab'' ({{lang-bn|বসন্ত উৎসব }}; ''Spring Festival''). 

== Names ==
In [[Bengali language|Bengali]], Pahela stands for 'first' and 'Falgun' or '''Fagun''<nowiki/>' is eleventh month of the [[Bengali calendar]].

